Problem 1¶

Rotating Machinery Diagnosis with Logistic Regression

Mechanical systems are always vibrating when operating. So, vibration analysis is one of the most popular and conventional ways to diagnose the mechanical system. In this problem, we are going to use the logistic regression algorithm to identify abnormality of a mechanical system.

Data information

  • File format: npy

  • Information: signal, label

  • Sampling rate: 12,800 Hz

  • File length (time): 0.78 sec

  • Labels based on one-hot encoding

    • A (Normal): [1,0]
    • B (Abnormal): [0,1]

  • label

Now, we need to extract features from the raw signal.

  • Use the following statistical features
    • peak, rms, kurtosis, crest factor, impulse factor, shape factor, skewness, smr, peak-peak

The equations are as follows:

$$\begin{align*} \text{Peak Value } &= \max_{n = 1, \dots, N} x_n \\ \\ \text{RMS } &= \sqrt{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N x_n^2} \\ \\ \text{Kurtosis } &= \frac{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N (x_n-\bar{x})^4}{\text{Var}^2} \\ \\ \text{Var } &= \frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N (x_n-\bar{x})^2 \\\\ \text{Crest Factor } &= \frac{\text{Peak}}{\text{RMS}}\\\\ \text{Impulse Factor } &= \frac{\text{Peak}}{\text{Mean}} \\ \\ \text{Mean } &= \frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N \lvert x_n \rvert \\\\ \text{Shape Factor } &= \frac{\text{RMS}}{\text{Mean}}\\\\ \text{Skewness } &= \frac{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N(x_n-\bar{x})^3}{\text{Var}^{3/2}}\\\\ \text{SMR } &= \left(\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N\sqrt{x_n} \right)^2 \\\\ \text{Peak-Peak Value } &= \max_{n = 1, \dots, N} x_n-\min_{n = 1, \dots, N} x_n \end{align*}$$$$x_i: \text{signal data}$$


The function for feature extraction is already ready for you. The function input and output are data $x$ and horizontally stacked feature vector, respectively.

In [4]:
def extfeat(x):
    fvector = []
   
    # time domain feature
    peak = np.max(np.abs(x))
    fvector.append(peak)
   
    rms = np.sqrt(np.mean(x**2))
    fvector.append(rms)
   
    kurtosis = scipy.stats.kurtosis(x)
    fvector.append(kurtosis)
   
    crest_factor = fvector[0]/fvector[1]
    fvector.append(crest_factor)
    
    impulse_factor = fvector[0]/(np.sum(np.abs(x))/len(x))
    fvector.append(impulse_factor)
    
    shape_factor = fvector[1]/(np.sum(np.abs(x))/len(x))
    fvector.append(shape_factor)

    skewness = scipy.stats.skew(x)
    fvector.append(skewness)
   
    smr = (np.sum(np.sqrt(np.abs(x)))/len(x))**2
    fvector.append(smr)
   
    pp = np.max(x) - np.min(x)
    fvector.append(pp)
   
    return fvector

feature_name = ['Peak', 'RMS', 'Kurtosis', 'Crest Factor', 'Impulse Factor','Shape Factor','Skewness','SMR', 'Peak-Peak']

Problem 2¶

Anomaly Detection with Autoencoder

Mechanical systems are always making vibration during it was operated. The vibration sensor is cheap enough as well as the vibrations are different for the different operating conditions. So, vibration analysis is one of the most popular and oldest ways to diagnosis the mechanical systems. Even if vibration analysis is very popular and cheap methods, vibration analysis is very hrad for non-expert workers. Raw signals look very similar and we need to study hundreads of cases of the mechanical systems.

In this problem, we are going to detect anomalies in the mechanical system by vibration data and AI.



Information of the Sensor Data and Anomalies:

This dataset (test data) contains 4 anomalies:

  • Misalignment of the pump and engine shaft (abruptly)
    • Instant defect appearing: 18:39:22
    • Instant defect disappearing: 18:42:32
  • Misalignment of pump and motor shaft (slow):
    • Slow defect appearing: 18:44:36-18:45:49
    • Instant defect disappearing: 18:46:51
  • Reduction of flow area section-1 (top):
    • Slow defect appearing: 19:06:57-19:07:37
    • Slow defect disappearing: 19:10:45-19:11:31
  • Reduction of flow area section-2 (bottom):
    • Slow defect appearing: 19:14:40-19:16:24
    • Slow defect disappearing: 19:19:15-19:21:16

Problem Solving Process

  1. You have to compress the information of the training data (normal) using an autoencoder.
  2. Generate predicted values for train data to ensure that the autoencoder compresses the sensor data information well.
  3. Predict the anomalies using the residual between the predicted value and the test data (ground truth). (Since the autoencoder learned from the train data, it will show a clear difference in the anomalies of the test data.)
